    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While you are taking the faucet apart, keep an eye out for a few common issues that can pop up inside the valve or in the pipes. One frequent problem is a corroded or misaligned valve seat, which can cause a leak even after you replace the washer. You might also find old, hardened gaskets or a cracked valve stem that needs replacing. If you notice any debris or rust in the valve body, use a small file or a brass brush to clean the seat and the inside of the valve before you install the new washer. It is also a good idea to check the rubber O-ring for cracks or tears, as these can lead to drips. If you encounter any unexpected obstructions, double-check that the faucet handle is fully unscrewed and that the valve stem is completely loose before you begin.",
